        "trailText":"<strong>Jonathan Freedland: First thoughts: </strong>It turns out Paxman shares Russell Brand's disillusion with politicians. But there are unelected people, wielding greater power, who rarely get the rotweiller treatment",
        "headline":"The question that Jeremy Paxman should ask himself",
        "body":"<p>So Jeremy Paxman and Russell Brand have more in common than fetching facial hair. It turns out that the Newsnight anchor agreed with the comedian more than he let on when <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3YR4CseY9pk\" title=\"\">the pair sparred in a YouTube-ready exchange</a> that centred on Brand's disillusion with the democratic process. \"I think part of Russell Brand's diagnosis is right,\" <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/nov/05/paxman-politics-russell-brand-voting\" title=\"\">Paxman confesses</a> in the latest edition of the Radio Times. \"There is a huge sense of disillusion out there.\"</p><p></p><p>Some will react to that the way they would to a complaint by Miley Cyrus about the sexualisation of young female musicians: you should know, because you're part of the problem. For if politicians are held in low regard, if not outright contempt, then some responsibility surely belongs to those from the rottweiler school of interviewing who cannot look at an elected official without dripping disdain. Those who watch Paxman, or listen to the Today programme's John Humphrys, can hardly be blamed for picking up some of that cynical attitude to the Westminster classes, which regards anyone who's won an election as automatically suspect. Recall Paxman's <a href=\"http://www.screenonline.org.uk/people/id/571500/\" title=\"\">description of his own mindset</a> when interviewing a politician: \"I am always asking myself why is this lying bastard lying to me?\"</p><p></p><p>Don't get me wrong: I'm not calling for Paxman or Humphrys to pull in their claws. Those in power merit forensic, unrelenting scrutiny. The problem is the definition of power. Paxman seems to believe the only authority that deserves the full Paxo treatment is the elected variety. He tends to reserve the trademark sneer, loaded first question and presumption of guilt for members of parliament and ministers – even those who, truth be told, wield only the most modest modicum of influence.</p><p></p><p>Rare is the occasion when he shows similar venom to those who wield unelected power. Watch the compilation of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jun/27/jeremy-paxmans-greatest-clips\" title=\"\">Paxo's greatest hits</a> and they consist chiefly of the grand inquisitor shredding politicians. Look for a similar encounter with a corporate titan, the heads of one of those companies or banks that exert vast influence over the national or global economy, and you will struggle. If it's happened once or twice, it's the exception not the rule. The likes of former junior minister <a href=\" http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=\"bddWaHuxTzc\"\" title=\"\">Chloe Smith</a> have more to fear from Paxman than the likes of Google's Eric Schmidt.</p><p></p><p>This problem goes far beyond the Newsnight presenter. Our media cover Westminster politics at a thousand times the intensity and detail with which it covers big business. Yet are our politicians really so much more powerful than the banks, the tech giants and the bond markets?</p><p></p><p>The usual defence for such aggressive interrogation is that this or that person is \"elected\" and therefore deserves to be held to the highest possible standard. The implication is that they would deserve it less if they were unelected. But this is surely the wrong way around. It is unelected, unaccountable power that needs more scrutiny. As, to his credit, Paxman himself concedes in his Radio Times article, elected politicians are, in fact, our only potential brake on power being \"wielded by the rich and strong for the benefit of the rich and strong\".</p><p></p><p>If too many people have lost sight of that democratic truth, regarding anyone who stands for elected office as a power-crazed weirdo and compulsive liar, then Paxman might put this tough question to himself, <a href=\" http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=\"Uwlsd8RAoqI#t=19\"\" title=\"\">asking it 12 times over if necessary</a>: \"Do you really believe you played no part whatsoever in this process, one you yourself now regret?\"</p><p></p><p><em>Twitter: </em><a href=\"https://twitter.com/Freedland\" title=\"\"><em>@Freedland</em></a></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421703535|2013-11-05T16:06:57Z|92792c2a2edfa51866c08b644c969d1a32411ae5 -->",
