        "trailText":"<strong>Rhiannon Lucy Cosslett:</strong> I've never really understood the antipathy towards onesies – toasty comfort surely trumps style when you get behind a British front door?",
        "headline":"Give the cashmere onesie a warm welcome",
        "body":"<p>Having announced a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/nov/05/marks-and-spencer-sales-fall\" title=\"\">drop in clothing sales of 1.3%</a> this morning, I can't help but wonder if <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/nov/05/marks-and-spencer-sales-fall\" title=\"\">Marks &amp; Spencer</a> might be pinning all its hopes on its new <a href=\"http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/columns/olivia-bergin/TMG10426789/Why-MandSs-cashmere-onesie-will-be-top-of-my-Christmas-list.html\" title=\"\">£199 luxury cashmere onesie</a>, released just in time for the Christmas gift guides. Considering one can pick up a fleece number from Primark for just over a tenner, you might argue that it's a bold move, but I think you'd be underestimating the British enthusiasm for toasty comfort.</p><p>The introduction of the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2012/jan/16/ever-ok-to-wear-onesie\" title=\"\">onesie</a> has seen the loungewear market explode, to the point where a pair of <a href=\"http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/galleries/TMG9226828/1/Urban-Legends.html\" title=\"\">£295 Penelope Chilvers slippers</a> have become the year's fashion must-haves. Previously limited to those ladies of leisure who spent their divorce settlements from Russian oligarchs lying around their Belgravia mansions like velveteen cats, loungewear is now available to the masses and, taking into account the high unemployment rate and the soaring costs of heating bills, you can see why.</p><p>I've never really understood the antipathy towards onesies – it seems to be a generational thing, signifying a postwar discomfort with comfort itself, rooted in a time where chilblains carried hipster kudos (they had a similar disdain for the shellsuit). I've never heard anyone under 30 disparage the onesie – as anyone who's ever slept in one will tell you, they are bloody warm (I spent most of last Christmas in my dinosaur one, and happily it doubles up as a Halloween costume, although one has to be careful to ascertain the location of the tail before going to the lavatory).</p><p>I'd go as far to say that a snugglier nap time cannot be had, and I come from a family of blanket wearers. Once inside my house, outdoor clothes are cast away in favour of a variety of items chosen for their place on the cosiness scale, with no attention being paid to their eccentricity. Hence why I usually jettison the silk slips and kimonos that would be sported by my ideal, glamorous self, in favour of some combination of the following items: a floor-length woolly Aran sweater smock that falls to my ankles (provenance unknown); a pair of fleecy pyjama bottoms three sizes two big which are a vision in black and white cow print (despite my mother forbidding me from wearing them in front of any member of the male sex lest I die a spinster); a reversible turquoise polar bear jumper; and a pair of novelty slippers that look like monster feet. And that's before we even start discussing headgear (fur, usually).</p><p>But it's par for the course when you grew up in the country. Having visited friends and family and caught them \"chillaxing\" in similar get-ups, it really does call the British taste into question. You wouldn't catch a French woman dead in multicoloured arm-warmers. All of which has convinced me that this garment is very much needed. Indeed, I'd go so far as suggesting that the government stop investing so much in winter fuel allowance and start handing these out to pensioners instead. The initial investment is worth it if it socks one to the energy companies. It'll certainly be on my Christmas list. My energy company's just switched my tariff?</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421700100|2013-11-05T16:06:57Z|bd6fe250969f2569032d052eb8a764351d7c24de -->",
